legacyCollection.name: Asia Pacific
legacyCollection.longDescription: The latest news and investigations from Asia, including China, India, Japan, Myanmar, North Korea, South Korea, Vietnam, Indonesia, Malaysia and Cambodia.

headline.default: Aboard the Star Ferry in Hong Kong

node.summary: The Star Ferry in Hong Kong has been offering an exhilarating ride for 142 years. Experience a trip with a Times reporter.

headline.default: Your Friday Briefing: Putin’s Defensive Speech

node.summary: The Russian leader claimed victory in Mariupol, despite Ukrainian resistance.

headline.default: Jimmy Wang Yu, Seminal Figure in Kung Fu Films, Dies at 79

node.summary: He changed the nature of Asian martial arts movies, which had been relying on sword fighting and fantasy, by bringing hand-to-hand combat to the fore.

headline.default: S​outh Korea’s Supreme Court ​Issues Landmark Ruling on Gay Sex

node.summary: ​The court said that the military should not punish consensual sex acts that had taken place in a nonmilitary setting.

headline.default: Explosion at Afghan Mosque Kills at Least 10

bylines.renderedRepresentation: By Yaqoob Akbary and Thomas Gibbons-Neff

node.summary: The blast in Mazar-i-Sharif, one of Afghanistan’s economic hubs, was the latest in a series of attacks on one of its religious minorities and was claimed by an ISIS affiliate.

headline.default: Why Are Kangaroos Turning Up in India?

bylines.renderedRepresentation: By Mike Ives and Sameer Yasir

node.summary: The animals are the latest exotic fauna to be smuggled into the country, possibly to be used as pets. Draft legislation would close loopholes in the roaring wildlife trade.

headline.default: Your Thursday Briefing: Russia Threatens Escalation

node.summary: Plus the emergence of armed militias in Colombia and questions over China’s Covid death toll.

headline.default: Tesla’s profits jumped in the first quarter, but challenges loom.

node.summary: The electric carmaker had to close an important factory in Shanghai because of China’s efforts to stamp out a coronavirus outbreak.

headline.default: The Plastic Paradise of Tokyo’s Famous Kitchen Town

node.summary: There is an estimated multibillion-dollar market in Japan for food you can't eat. The craftsmanship can be extraordinary.

headline.default: Myanmar faces a health emergency as its military regime targets doctors.
6 Rohingya Refugees Are Killed Fleeing Detention Center in Malaysia

node.summary: In recent years, the Malaysian government has taken a more hard-line approach to the refugees in the country, which once offered a modicum of opportunity.

headline.default: Shanghai’s Low Covid Death Toll Revives Questions About China’s Numbers

bylines.renderedRepresentation: By Vivian Wang, Joy Dong and Amy Chang Chien

node.summary: The country’s largest city has recorded just 17 Covid deaths, despite surging cases. How China defines a Covid death may be part of the reason.

headline.default: Your Wednesday Briefing: Russia Bombards the East

node.summary: Moscow’s military offensive in eastern Ukraine has begun.

headline.default: Star Ferry, ‘Emblem of Hong Kong,’ May Sail Into History After 142 Years

node.summary: Launched in 1880, the ferry has witnessed both Hong Kong’s transformation into a global financial hub and its history of protests. But battered by a pandemic, the service is struggling to survive.

headline.default: Explosions at Schools in Kabul Kill at Least 6

bylines.renderedRepresentation: By The Associated Press and Reuters

node.summary: Blasts outside an education center and a public high school in Afghanistan’s capital killed at least six people and wounded several students. No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attacks.

headline.default: Blasts at Schools in Shiite Area of Kabul Kill at Least 6

bylines.renderedRepresentation: By Christina Goldbaum and Yaqoob Akbary

node.summary: More than a dozen people were also wounded, one as young as 7. The attacks again challenged the Taliban’s promise of security, and stoked deep-seated fears in the Shiite community.

headline.default: A Quiet Intensity, Matched With Big Ambitions

node.summary: Joe Kahn, the next executive editor of The New York Times, has had a steady rise in journalism. It began with a decision to turn his focus to China.

headline.default: Working From Home, Japan’s Corporate Warriors Rethink Their Priorities

node.summary: The country’s traditional job-for-life model is eroding, with pressure now coming from workers who want more flexibility, autonomy and control over their careers.

headline.default: Myanmar’s Health System Is in Collapse, ‘Obliterated’ by the Regime

node.summary: The country is also now one of the most dangerous places in the world to be a medical worker. At least 30 doctors have been killed since the coup, a rights group says.

headline.default: Your Tuesday Briefing: Russia Launches Assault in Eastern Ukraine

node.summary: Plus China’s lockdowns slow its economy and France’s candidates vie for undecided voters.
